an, Erez, Faina, Haya, Mendel.  Russian Leonid, Aleksandr, Boris, Feiga, Genady.","Jewish (from Russia): variant of   Gordon   5.","French: variant of   Gourdin  . This surname is very rare in France."]},{"name":"Gordan","meanings":["German: variant of   Jordan  . The surname <i>Gordan</i> is very rare in Germany.","Irish (Wexford and Sligo): adopted as an Anglicized form of <b>Mag Mhuirneacháin</b> ‘son of <i>Muirneachán</i>’, a personal name from a diminutive of <i>muirneach</i> ‘lovable’."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Thomas de Gordon, Knight, 3rd Laird of Gordon was born about 1183, in Gordon, Berwickshire, Scotland, his father, Sir Richard de Gordon, de Swinton 2nd Lord of Gordon in the Merse, was 55 and his mother, Mrs Richard De Gordon, was 49. He married Mrs Thomas De Gordon. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died about 1260, in his hometown, at the age of 79."},"et":{"about 1183–about 1260":"umbes 1183–umbes 1260","1183–1260":"1183–1260","1185–Female":"1185–Surnud","1214–1259":"1214–1259","1130–1200":"1130–1200","1135–Female":"1135–Surnud","about 1183":"umbes 1183","about 1260":"umbes 1260","1259":"1259","1214":"1214","28 August 1259":"28. august 1259","1135":"1135","1200":"1200","1130":"1130","1185":"1185","1260":"1260","1183":"1183","1182":"1182","Gordon Berwickshire, Berwick, Scotland":"Gordon, Berwickshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Gordon, Berwickshire, Scotland":"Gordon, Berwickshire, Scotland","Swinton, Berwickshire, 